K-Means Clustering to Get Player Recommendation

Objective:

OnSports is a fantasy sports platform that has fantasy leagues for many different sports and has witnessed an increasing number of participants globally over the past 5 years. For each player, a price is set at the start, and the price keeps changing over time based on the performance of the players in the real world. With the new English Premier League season about to start, they have collected data from the past season and want to analyze it to determine the price of each player for the start of the new season. OnSports have hired you as a data scientist and asked you to conduct a cluster analysis to identify players of different potentials of each player based on previous season performance. This will help them understand the patterns in player performances and fantasy returns and decide the exact price to be set for each player for the upcoming football season.

Data Variables:

  • Player_Name: Name of the player.
  • Club: Club in which the player plays.
  • Position: Position in which the player plays.
  • Goals_Scored: Number of goals scored by the player in the previous season.
  • Assists: Number of passes made by the player leading to goals in the previous season.
  • Total_Points: Total number of fantasy points scored by the player in the previous season.
  • Minutes: Number of minutes played by the player in the previous season.
  • Goals_Conceded: Number of goals conceded by the player in the previous season.
  • Creativity: A score, computed using a range of stats, that assesses player performance in terms of producing goalscoring opportunities for other players.
  • Influence: A score, computed using a range of stats, that evaluates a player's impact on a match, taking into account actions that could directly or indirectly affect the match outcome.
  • Threat: A score, computed using a range of stats, that gauges players who are most likely to score goals.
  • Bonus: Total bonus points received. The three best performing players in each match receive additional bonus points based on a score computed using a range of stats. 3 points are awarded to the highest scoring player, 2 to the second best, and 1 to the third.
  • Clean_Sheets: Number of matches without conceding a goal in the previous season.

#Creating barplots for categorical variables:

# Function to create labeled barplots


def labeled_barplot(df, feature, perc = False, n = None):
    """
    Barplot with percentage at the top

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    perc: whether to display percentages instead of count (default is False)
    n: displays the top n category levels (default is None, i.e., display all levels)
    """

    total = len(df[feature])  # Length of the column
    count = df[feature].nunique()
    if n is None:
        plt.figure(figsize = (count + 1, 5))
    else:
        plt.figure(figsize = (n + 1, 5))

    plt.xticks(rotation = 90, fontsize = 15)
    ax = sns.countplot(
        data = df,
        x = feature,
        palette = "viridis",
        order = df[feature].value_counts().index[:n].sort_values(),
    )

    for p in ax.patches:
        if perc == True:
            label = "{:.1f}%".format(
                100 * p.get_height() / total
            )  # Percentage of each class of the category
        else:
            label = p.get_height()  # Count of each level of the category

        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2  # Width of the plot
        y = p.get_height()  # Height of the plot

        ax.annotate(
            label,
            (x, y),
            ha = "center",
            va = "center",
            size = 12,
            xytext = (0, 5),
            textcoords = "offset points",
        )  # Annotate the percentage

    plt.show()  # Show the plot

#Empty dictionary to store distortions

AvgDistortion = {}
In[182]:
#Iterate for a range of Ks and fit the scaled data to the algorithm
#Use inertia attribute from kmeans object and store the inertia value for that k

for k in range(1,15):

    model = KMeans(n_clusters = k, random_state = 42, n_init = "auto")

    model.fit(df_pca)

    prediction = model.predict(k_means_df)

    distortion = (
        sum(np.min(cdist(k_means_df, model.cluster_centers_, "euclidean"), axis = 1))
        / k_means_df.shape[0]
    )

    AvgDistortion[k] = distortion

In[189]:
# Empty dictionary to store the Silhouette score for each value of K
sc = {}

# Iterate for a range of Ks and fit the scaled data to the algorithm. Store the Silhouette score for that K
for k in range(3, 15):
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters = k, random_state = 42, n_init='auto').fit(df_pca)

    labels = kmeans.predict(df_pca)

    sc[k] = silhouette_score(df_pca, labels)

# Elbow plot
plt.figure()

plt.plot(list(sc.keys()), list(sc.values()), 'bx-')

plt.xlabel("Number of cluster")

plt.ylabel("Silhouette Score")

Conclusions about each cluster

  • Cluster 0: There are 254 players on cluster 0. The players on this group appears to be low performers when comparing to the other players and do not present impressive scores on the performance metrics.
  • Cluster 1: There are 76 players on this cluster. When compared to players in cluster 2, these players seem to have better performance in terms of Goals_Scored, Assists, and Threat.
  • Cluster 2: There are 104 players in cluster 2. This group of players seems to be composed of average players, but stands out in terms of minutes played, Influence, and clean sheets. It also has a great amount of goals conceded, which suggests a problem in performance.
  • Cluster 3: There are 42 players on cluster 3. These players definetely appear to be the top performers in the dataset and are the players that should be considered for a higher price. This cluster stands out from all the other clusters in terms of performance and has the highest scores for key performance variables such as Total_Points, Goals Scored, Bonus, Threat, Influence, and Creativity.

In[206]:
# Initializing K-Means
kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters = 4, random_state = 42, n_init = 'auto')

# Fitting and predicting K-Means on df_pca
predict = kmeans.fit_predict((df_pca))

score = silhouette_score(df_pca, predict)

print('Silhouette Score:', score)

Silhouette Score: 0.4430152162896188

Conlusion:

The silhouette score is used to assess clustering model performance. The K-Means algorithm presented a silhouette score of 0.44, which indicates that this model did a good job in grouping the data points to appropriate clusters.
